yours live. Yeah. That would be. Hey, Logan. How's it going? It's all right. I wanted to ask,

00:38:52.263 --> 00:38:55.944
I'm a little young in my career as a data scientist. So I wanted to ask, it seems like

00:38:55.944 --> 00:39:01.623
you've switched a lot of careers where data is vastly different. The systems that you're using

00:39:01.623 --> 00:39:09.223
are vastly different. And as data scientists, we're expected to know, be the experts on our

00:39:09.223 --> 00:39:15.624
systems and data. How do you quickly become an expert on the, when you walk into a new job,

00:39:15.624 --> 00:39:24.103
how do you quickly become the data expert? I don't think there's any such thing as quickly

00:39:24.103 --> 00:39:34.904
becoming a data expert. So the way I grew into my role is I, so if this is a funnel, I'd say here,

00:39:34.904 --> 00:39:39.943
if this is a funnel here is where data scientists usually operate. And I'd say, stop just being

00:39:39.943 --> 00:39:45.464
here. This is a local minima for you. Just don't be here. Which is why I say, if you think like

00:39:45.464 --> 00:39:52.184
a architect system design comes into the picture, you have to know where your data exists, what's

00:39:52.184 --> 00:39:56.424
your data pipeline. So depending on whichever company that you work for, try and get to know

00:39:56.424 --> 00:40:01.144
the data pipeline. If you don't have restrictions to know that data pipeline or to access that

00:40:01.144 --> 00:40:07.624
thing, that's a different issue. And it makes it much easier, but get to know that, where all of

00:40:07.624 --> 00:40:13.383
the data is flowing into, what kind of data does my company get in? If you want to call it a data

00:40:13.383 --> 00:40:19.383
lake, what flows into the data lake and outside of the data lake, what kind of pipelines are built

00:40:19.383 --> 00:40:26.263
to go into relational databases or NoSQL kind of setting, or am I just feeding into flat files or

00:40:26.263 --> 00:40:30.744
am I, if you work in industries where there are images or audio files and stuff like that.

00:40:31.703 --> 00:40:37.943
And then you'll have to start thinking about, if I have to collect more features for whatever

00:40:37.943 --> 00:40:44.024
data science work that I'm doing, can I extract features only from this relational database or

00:40:44.024 --> 00:40:48.983
from NoSQL, or can I also go above and beyond and say, you know what, from this particular

00:40:48.983 --> 00:40:55.624
WAV file, I can actually transcribe this document, this audio file, and then do some NLP on top of

00:40:55.624 --> 00:41:01.064
that, or basically if you're using a language model to be able to summarize or to extract,

00:41:01.064 --> 00:41:05.943
can I get more data points out of that? Is this information available? That is kind of how you

00:41:05.943 --> 00:41:11.703
have to think, because you should never stop yourself in this here. You also have to

00:41:11.703 --> 00:41:15.783
think about a data engineer. You have to think about, okay, but if I have to connect these two

00:41:15.783 --> 00:41:20.744
different databases, how do I go about connecting them? Am I writing the most optimal SQL?

00:41:20.744 --> 00:41:24.424
And then once you connect different databases, you'll try and say, oh, these have these many other

00:41:24.424 --> 00:41:28.904
fields that I didn't know. You'll have to spend time visually looking at all of the different

00:41:28.904 --> 00:41:33.304
fields and see if it's useful to you or not. You'll have to be very curious and asking

00:41:33.624 --> 00:41:38.983
same question as to what does this mean? What does that mean? And then most importantly,

00:41:38.983 --> 00:41:46.024
I would say you'll have to think like the business or like your end user. If you were

00:41:46.024 --> 00:41:51.783
a recipient of the analysis that you were given, what would you want or what else do you want?

00:41:52.503 --> 00:41:58.823
How deep would you want to go? And so that's kind of how you have to switch your thinking.

00:41:58.823 --> 00:42:04.503
So your data science, with all of the machine learning and the statistics background that you

00:42:04.503 --> 00:42:10.503
must have learned in your school, or even when you're in your job that you're learning, that

00:42:10.503 --> 00:42:22.024
you're being an architect or a system designer, and then being a vertical data engineer is

00:42:22.024 --> 00:42:27.864
fundamental to being a good machine learning stack. Then if you want to add yourself another

00:42:27.864 --> 00:42:32.103
vertical, which is DevOps, that's great. It's not necessarily going to build you with anything,

00:42:32.103 --> 00:42:36.263
but let's say if you want to become the CTO of a company, you will have that thought process

00:42:36.263 --> 00:42:40.344
where you say, I want you to do X, Y, and Z and think about this. I want to solution this and so

00:42:40.344 --> 00:42:44.823
on and so forth. So that's kind of how I would say grow into your career in that perspective and not

00:42:44.823 --> 00:42:49.543
just limit yourself to just being, I was given this data. I'm only going to look at these features

00:42:49.543 --> 00:42:57.624
and based on these features, here's the output. So like I said, go and look for data that you

00:42:57.624 --> 00:43:02.263
probably don't even think you need for right now. Just look at the data, like see what's

00:43:02.263 --> 00:43:07.943
available. And then you'll know that, okay, when the time comes, oh, I have this data over here,

00:43:07.943 --> 00:43:13.783
would that be useful? Or there is data over here, which is somewhat translatable to the

00:43:13.783 --> 00:43:18.824
feature that I'm looking for. Let me see and add that. That's kind of how I would go about it.

00:43:20.424 --> 00:43:26.103
We have lots of voting for yes, think like the business. And also I wanted to

00:43:26.103 --> 00:43:30.744
point out Hubert's comment in the chat, which was that understanding of the domain knowledge is

00:43:30.744 --> 00:43:35.783
super important. And people tend to just kind of skip that because of the deadline pressure

00:43:35.783 --> 00:43:40.903
that they get, but understanding the data and the domain is absolutely invaluable.

00:43:40.903 --> 00:43:46.343
Okay. Let's head over to Slido one more time and we only have 10 minutes left, but hopefully we

00:43:46.343 --> 00:43:53.624
can get another question and then talk a little bit about career advice. So one that might be

00:43:53.624 --> 00:43:57.704
quick to answer, we had an anonymous question that said, I've been told that I need to have

00:43:57.704 --> 00:44:03.223
a portfolio and I need to have done a bunch of projects on GitHub to be a stronger job-seeking

00:44:03.223 --> 00:44:14.744
candidate. How true is that? It is true to a certain extent, especially if you're in a tie

00:44:14.744 --> 00:44:22.424
break situation. So I've interviewed for people to be part of my team or to be part of other

00:44:22.824 --> 00:44:29.143
teams as well. That's my first thing that I look for is, do they have a GitHub profile?

00:44:29.143 --> 00:44:34.903
And what kind of work they've done? I'd like to see what kind of changes they've made over

00:44:34.903 --> 00:44:41.064
time, the comments that they do and stuff like that. But at the same time, it's more relevant

00:44:41.704 --> 00:44:51.064
if you are very early in your career. And let's say you're looking for a job and for whatever

00:44:51.064 --> 00:44:56.023
reason, you haven't been able to seek a job for six months. When you start on Jan 1st, let's say,

00:44:56.023 --> 00:44:59.783
nobody thinks that they'll have to wait until June or July to find a job. They would hope that

00:44:59.783 --> 00:45:05.384
they'd get a job sooner than later. But I just say, start on the side, building out projects

00:45:05.384 --> 00:45:12.103
that you think you're interested, not to show somebody else that you can do X, Y, and Z.

00:45:12.103 --> 00:45:17.463
But if it's a project that you think that you're genuinely interested, automatically you will go

00:45:17.463 --> 00:45:25.223
very deep into that. And when you talk about that in your job interview, you will then tell

00:45:25.223 --> 00:45:28.983
them how you thought through the problem, how you thought through the solutions, how you thought

00:45:28.983 --> 00:45:32.343
through the system design, if there is a system designed to that, how you thought through the

00:45:32.343 --> 00:45:39.944
scale of problem, how you thought through the lack of data, if it's data that's

00:45:40.663 --> 00:45:46.264
publicly available, and how did you get that data? How did you transform that data?

00:45:46.264 --> 00:45:51.944
All of those things will automatically happen. So even if it's just one project, the depth of

00:45:51.944 --> 00:45:57.304
the project is sufficient. And then you'll anyways have, depending on the team that you're

00:45:57.304 --> 00:46:05.304
interviewing with, the code that you work with, they'll ask you to write your code. So it's not

00:46:05.304 --> 00:46:11.064
a given that if you have a GitHub profile, they'll wave off the code interview part or something of

00:46:11.064 --> 00:46:16.663
that sort. You'll have a few more downy points here and there. But the way I look at interviewees

00:46:16.663 --> 00:46:21.624
is how they are able to think, especially in this day and age when you have coding agents

00:46:22.424 --> 00:46:28.023
and the need to be an exceptionally good coder is kind of reduced. It's all about the way you

00:46:28.023 --> 00:46:32.103
think about a solution and the way you come up with the solutions. Have you been able to put

00:46:32.103 --> 00:46:37.223
out a dashboard of sorts? And all of those things do matter. So think about it that way and build

00:46:37.223 --> 00:46:42.903
up a site as well. Fantastic. Okay. Well, seven minutes left. So maybe we can get in

00:46:44.343 --> 00:46:49.783
our last question that we like to ask, which is career advice. There's been a ton of career

00:46:49.783 --> 00:46:53.543
advice already in our call, but Prajesh, are there some things that you would share with people

00:46:54.184 --> 00:46:59.143
who are sort of like lower down the ladder than you or your peers? Like

00:46:59.143 --> 00:47:02.264
what helped you in your career? What would you share with others?

00:47:03.143 --> 00:47:12.184
Like I said, when Logan was asking, don't put yourself in a local minimum. If that's what you

00:47:12.184 --> 00:47:15.864
want to do and you're happy in that space, that's fine. There's nothing wrong with that. There is no

00:47:15.864 --> 00:47:22.504
right or wrong things here. But if you are a curious person, if you want to grow up the ladder,

00:47:22.504 --> 00:47:27.944
even don't just put yourself in a local minimum. I have a bunch that I've kind of wanted to get

00:47:28.903 --> 00:47:34.504
into, but none of them are related to go to this particular website, this particular YouTube

00:47:34.504 --> 00:47:42.264
channel, or listen to this podcast and whatever. I think the first thing that you need to develop

00:47:42.264 --> 00:47:48.903
is perspective as a data scientist or a machine learning engineer or whatever. It's about

00:47:48.903 --> 00:47:56.583
developing new perspectives. You will have to spend your time and actively curate what perspectives

00:47:56.663 --> 00:48:08.663
that you develop and how that translates to what you do in your job. I very consciously built

00:48:08.663 --> 00:48:13.463
myself into thinking like a data scientist. I was a researcher, so I used to think like a

00:48:13.463 --> 00:48:17.704
researcher. And then I quickly realized that just thinking like that wouldn't help because there are

00:48:17.704 --> 00:48:21.783
deadlines to reach. There are so many other things, not every job, not every problem is a research

00:48:21.783 --> 00:48:27.944
problem. So you'll start having to think about what is the simplest way I can get to the solution.

00:48:27.944 --> 00:48:32.744
If there is a simple way, do I even need to go and think about a more complex machine learning

00:48:32.744 --> 00:48:36.744
solution? Take it to the business. If the business is happy with that, okay, so be it.

00:48:36.744 --> 00:48:43.624
But then you kind of get a buy-in because I think a lot of people's issues are we are not really

00:48:43.624 --> 00:48:49.064
given enough time to implement X, Y, and Z. Initially, you will never be given enough time,

00:48:49.064 --> 00:48:53.624
but then you get a buy-in after producing some results and then tell them, hey, usually this is

00:48:53.624 --> 00:48:57.944
not a good thing for X, Y, and Z reasons. You have to do all of these things, which usually takes

00:48:58.663 --> 00:49:03.064
three months instead of the two or one month that you asked for. And so you're kind of

00:49:04.424 --> 00:49:09.543
buying more territory based on how you go about it. And for that, you need to know

00:49:10.103 --> 00:49:13.543
the different verticals and the different horizontals and how they work. If somebody

00:49:13.543 --> 00:49:20.264
says scale up, I want you to be able to do this for a million documents. You have to make them

00:49:20.264 --> 00:49:24.343
understand that from a DevOps perspective, it's not just random scale up. It comes with certain

00:49:24.343 --> 00:49:31.624
costs. You won't be expected to see the same amount of time and accuracy because of certain

00:49:31.624 --> 00:49:36.583
things that you would probably see something in a thousand documents versus a million documents.

00:49:36.583 --> 00:49:43.384
And it changes the way systems are interconnected. It could potentially induce more failures. It

00:49:43.384 --> 00:49:49.864
would potentially induce more missed documents or whatever. So you'll have to talk to them about it.

00:49:49.864 --> 00:49:54.903
Usually many people in the business are willing to listen to your things, but at the same time,

00:49:54.903 --> 00:50:03.384
keep it somewhat technical. So you have to learn to speak like the business and explain in English

00:50:03.384 --> 00:50:08.343
rather than going too technical about X, Y, and Z, which they may or may not necessarily fully

00:50:08.343 --> 00:50:15.223
understand. So go vertical and go horizontal at the same time if you want to really be

00:50:15.223 --> 00:50:20.983
exceptionally good at your job. That's my long and short of career advice. But outside of that,

00:50:20.983 --> 00:50:26.903
I have a few that I'd like to go through. First and foremost, be kind. That's the first thing

00:50:26.903 --> 00:50:32.264
that you should do. Be kind to people. And as a data scientist or a machine learning engineer,

00:50:32.264 --> 00:50:37.064
you have to train yourself to be unbiased. What that means to say is you have to

00:50:37.864 --> 00:50:44.023
stop thinking of this works. I know I have so much experience, blah, blah, blah. Put all of

00:50:44.023 --> 00:50:49.384
that aside when you get into a meeting with someone. Hear them out. Don't talk over them

00:50:49.384 --> 00:50:56.983
and hear them out and understand what they're trying to say. Many times when we go and sit

00:50:57.864 --> 00:51:03.944
with the business is we try and get the requirements. The getting the requirements

00:51:03.944 --> 00:51:09.143
part is more like the business says these nine things are my requirements. Am I delivering on

00:51:09.143 --> 00:51:13.624
that? No. There's a lot of in between the lines. So try and understand what the business really

00:51:13.624 --> 00:51:18.583
wants. Sometimes the business doesn't really know what they want. So try and talk to them about it.

00:51:18.583 --> 00:51:22.903
Try and work through that thing. And then you can then get a better business requirements.

00:51:23.543 --> 00:51:27.463
And then when you work with your business analyst or whoever is writing the business requirements,

00:51:27.463 --> 00:51:32.103
you can say, Hey, this is probably not going to be done in this phase because of these reasons,

00:51:32.103 --> 00:51:37.064
but we can do an approximation of this. So on and so forth. So it just depends on how you

00:51:38.103 --> 00:51:44.983
genuinely listen to people. If you're interested, be a mentor, becoming a mentor or becoming a

00:51:44.983 --> 00:51:50.184
teacher changes the perspective altogether in the way you actually go about your own job.

00:51:50.663 --> 00:51:54.503
Because then there's a difference between you understanding something and there's a difference

00:51:54.503 --> 00:51:59.224
between you explaining something. And then like Feynman or Einstein, either of them said,

00:51:59.224 --> 00:52:03.783
if you're not able to explain something adequately, you haven't understood it well enough.

00:52:03.783 --> 00:52:13.143
So being a mentor to somebody who's a junior or not as much experience as you are always helps.

00:52:13.143 --> 00:52:16.344
And they bring in new perspectives that you probably never would have thought of.

00:52:16.344 --> 00:52:20.743
So that's something that you would have to definitely look into. And I think this is

00:52:20.743 --> 00:52:25.704
extremely important for data scientists, develop rapport with people and get them to invite you

00:52:25.704 --> 00:52:31.143
into meetings that you have no business being in. Just sit there and listen to what they are

00:52:31.143 --> 00:52:36.104
discussing, especially if it is business related, because you will then understand why business is

00:52:36.104 --> 00:52:40.663
asking for something rather than what they're specifically asking for. So just go there.

00:52:40.663 --> 00:52:44.584
I used to do this. I used to just say, Hey, can I just join here? And then I just, I used to sit

00:52:44.584 --> 00:52:48.184
there. I used to say, I used to say, can I be a fly in the wall? And they'd be like, okay,

00:52:48.184 --> 00:52:53.383
CC Brijesh. And I just go and listen. And I developed so many perspectives. That's kind

00:52:53.383 --> 00:52:59.304
of how I developed my know-how of some of the domain knowledge. Otherwise you won't get that

00:52:59.304 --> 00:53:04.023
domain knowledge. You will then hear more problems in the business than you think, Oh, you know what?

00:53:04.023 --> 00:53:08.903
I can actually solve for this. That gives you some more acceptance and buy-in as well in the

00:53:08.903 --> 00:53:14.023
company that you are working for. Fantastic. Well, we have hit the top of the hour.

00:53:14.023 --> 00:53:18.023
So I have to jump in and stop you Brijesh, but please follow Brijesh on LinkedIn,

